First SparkR Notebook

This small example is taken almost verbatim from sparklyr R interface for Apache Spark.

Begin by loading the library and ensure Spark version 1.6.1 is installed

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(sparklyr)
spark_install(version = "1.6.1")

Create a Spark context

sc <- spark_connect(master = "local")

This Spark instance can be monitored in the Spark tab. So, lets load some data

iris_tbl <- copy_to(sc, iris)
flights_tbl <- copy_to(sc, nycflights13::flights, "flights")
batting_tbl <- copy_to(sc, Lahman::Batting, "batting")

List all the tables in the Spark context

src_tbls(sc)
## [1] "batting" "flights" "iris"

Now, chose all flights that were delayed 2 (hours?) in departure

flights_tbl %>% filter(dep_delay == 2)

Well, lets make a graphic that shows a delay and distance. First create the data set to visualise

delay <- flights_tbl %>% 
   group_by(tailnum) %>% 
   summarise(count = n(), dist = mean(distance), delay = mean(arr_delay)) %>% 
   filter(count > 20, dist < 2000, !is.na(delay)) %>% 
   collect

and create the plot

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(delay, aes(dist, delay)) +
   geom_point(aes(size = count), alpha = 1/2) +
   geom_smooth() +
   scale_size_area(max_size = 2)
